The problem is that a German original translated to French translated to English.

"L´armee de ceux qui sont tombeés n´a pas rendu les armes,elle marche das le rang des soldats"

this could be roughly translated as
"the army of those who have fallen, has not put down (or back) its weapons, it marches within the ranks of our soldiers"

For anyone interested in Germany it is very well known that the Horst Wessel Lied and main symbolisms used by Goebbels are tighly linked with each other.

Maybe not, and maybe I’m very naive, but I don’t consider myself particularly intelligent or sophisticated or knowledgeable; there’s hardly anything special about me or anyone else for listening to this stuff.

I struggle to imagine that anyone is incapable of enjoying music that’s complex or intricate or busy or harmonically unusual, when ultimately the things that make something like Gentle Giant fun and appealing are the same things that make most music appealing.

I suppose music has always driven my curiosity - i.e I discover you can do THIS crazy thing with sound, and want to figure out what about it does things to me, and then I want to discover some other thing, and some other thing, and then next thing I’m crying listening to noise music.

Maybe that much makes a difference between what people let themselves find beauty in, but I don’t think it’s any real reflection of who someone is.

I'm beginning to feel that Share Threads are a mistake and should be discontinued.

Even when people do go out of their way to share music, there's always somebody who comes along to ruin it for the rest of us. They either criticize what's been posted without posting anything themselves, giving the orignal uploader a hard time they don't deserve, or they get down right vicious with people requesting music. Does it really matter if anybody doesn't have the music? I mean if you don't have the music, don't respond, and if you do respond, at least be polite, and just indicate that you can't help that person, but the attacks have been getting quite ugly and are undeserved. And then, in the last thread when somebody had uploaded some music and made a request, somebody had downloaded the music, thanked them for posting what they did.and apologized for the fact that they didn't have what they requested, one or more people acted like it was the same person and started accusing both of them of "Samefagging" when, in fact it was two different people, and not the same person.

If people were going to share music freely, that would be one thing, if people can't fulfill a request, and were polite about it, that would be find, but lately these thread are no longer about that. They have become very mean spirited and very ugly.

I think of people can't simply share music, and if people can't express their opinions about what's shared in a polite way, and if people are just going to be downright mean and rude for whatever reason, then maybe its time for the administrators to bring shrarethreads to an end!

I'm sick and tired of people posting music, and somebody criticizing them for their selection! I'm sick and tired of people picking on somebody for requesting music. I'm sick and tired of all the criticisms and all the trolls who are the catalysts and participants in the nasty behavior. Sharethreads are quickly degenerating to SHIT THREADS!

>>114642329
People like to disregard the enormous pedigree and culture dubstep actually has. First off dubstep is a evolution of A: dub reggae, sound system culture, UK garage, and all of it's forms encapsulate this pedigree. Dubstep continues the spirit of sound system culture by pushing boundaries in sound design and sub frequency with some songs peaking at 0 lufts pushing Henessy and funkington1 sound systems to their limit. "Real" dubstep, aka UK dub continues the spirit of dub itself in a pure form you can hear why dubstep became actually popular and was considered cool in the UK by listening to something like: Alix perez - melodrama, a very dark garage influenced dubstep track. I guess what I'm trying to say is that this genre has nothing to do with fucking break beat lol. Fucking dumbass. And it has real cultural roots it's not just some cheap garbage like everyone thinks it is. Some of the engineering and sound design in good dubstep approaches the highest in the echelon competing with the likes of amon Tobin or noisia. Although there is a shit ton of cringe dubstep and it is very much the numetal of electronic which is actually awesome much like hardstyle jumpstyle and so on.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114643336
2/2

IMO unless you have a really specific aim like "make a UK bass that's somehow new and sounds really exciting", you'll eventually start to view "best sound design" as entirely subjective or otherwise not very interesting. If it's objective, it's just whatever sounds you haven't heard before because they're being made with new technology. Cool while it still sounds new but pretty quickly it just becomes another piece of musical lego like all the rest. At that point all you can really do is say about "sound design" is which sounds you like the most. Personally I really like a lot of modular sounds from the techno world

but a lot of perception of a "cool sound" has to do with how the music has prepared you for the arrival of that sound / the immediate context of the sound, including the emotional arc of the music (and meaning arc is there are lyrics or other content somehow associated with the music)

e.g. the minimoog lead sound that comes in around 13:50 in Close to the Edge
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=51oPKLSuyQY

If you listen to the entire song the impact of that sound is earth shattering. It's just a minimoog lead anyone can make in 2 minutes who has a minimoog. If you just skip to it without the context it doesn't sound nearly as cool.

or here - The chord stabs that start showing up at 4:00 are fucking sweet. But if you just skip to it without listening to the track and establishing a context for your ear, it just sounds like any other flat block of saws.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=39IVwE-TP5Y

I dunno. Acoustic folk is sound design endgame if that's what does it for you once you've explored everything.

I was listening to Tour by Macky Gee 17 times in a row, and I came across a number of people talking shit on him and this genre they call 'jump up'. I listened to many examples of """good""" DnB and other similar genres and all of them bored me shitless. The sound design is great and the layering is is dense and complex and the songs are fucking tedious.

The thing about music is it's not about making sounds that sound good, but rather making sounds that make you feel good. Or even sad or whatever, but just feel something. When that bass comes in on Tour you just go oh fucking hell that is the one. It doesn't need to be some great intellectual pursuit, it has a predictable buildup and then just repeats the same fucking thing for like 4 minutes straight, and why???? Because it sounds fucking sick.

The electronic scene has lost sight of this. Everything is about retardedly complex sound design and no one ever actually makes engaging music with all these ridiculous sounds.

Since I'm blog posting I'll say how I came to this revelation. Years ago when I first started getting into DnB I was looking up what are considered the 'classics' of the genre. Most of them were kind of average and needed to be played on a huge sound system to really appreciate imo. Noisia was one of the artists I liked a lot then. Somewhere along the line I found Tour and it stood out to me among all others, then I subsequently forgot about it.

Fast forward to recent times and I was living with some fellows who would just leave DnB playlists on the whole time when we were getting mashed, and I heard that damn synth sound and just went oh shit that's the one. I made sure to find out what it was since I had forgotten.

So why that one instead of all the others? As I said before, it's not only me either, it's almost universal to anyone other than musical elitists who prioritize irrelevant things which is why no one likes them. I don't really have the answer to why aside from what I have said already.

The best rock equivalent I can think of is 96 Quite Bitter Beings by CKY. It's a dumb song, but the riff is one of the greatest ever so the song only needs to be just barely good enough to carry the rest of it, and everyone likes it as soon as they hear it.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aVdR6JeEyT8

It almost seems unfair, maybe they just got lucky? I don't really know.

NOISIA - THE TIDE https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GFag6Y_Nl5M

>>114640065
Because classical music stopped meaningfully developing new musical concepts at the same time as jazz began to do just that.

Yes there’s Boulez’s advancements in serialism or the crazy shit that Varez or Xenakis did, but there’s virtually theoretical or conceptual innovations in Western classical music past 1950 that could ever be of any use to an individual or small ensemble trying to make music that’s worth hearing.

Conversely at almost exactly the same point in time, bebop musicians were studying ideas and techniques from early twentieth-century and adapting them to their own ends, making sense of them within a jazz idiom, and developing their own independent theoretical frameworks. All of this was being done to the ends of making music people might actually want to hear; even some of the most extreme or chromatic (non-free) avant-garde jazz makes significantly more musical sense than most mid-to-late twentieth century classical.

Don’t get me wrong I love Stockhausen and all that shit, but it exactly really churn out musical ideas that are useful for coming up with chord progressions, riffs, and melodies.

>>114640798
>Classical music, or at least some European focused music, as opposed to latin/jazz.

“Classical music” as a phenomena is a pretty narrow thing, it’s basically just shy of 200 years of a few posh people writing music that was written in quite a harmonically rigid and rhythmically restrictive way. People can and did do utterly astonishing things within the horizons of their era, and by the late Romantic era (late19th/early20th century) began to stretch their own horizons to breaking point. But your Wagners or Lizsts relied so heavily on incredibly rarefied harmonic forms or technical virtuosity for its own sake that their innovations aren’t really all that adaptable to other kinds of music making.

There’s are exceptions to this - famously, mid-twentieth century innovators in jazz were very fond of composers like Debussy or Satie because of their emphasis on harmonic “colour” and nonfunctional harmony as expressive mediums in themselves; and also of certain composers such as Bartok or Stravinsky who explored Eastern European scales and rhythms previously alien to the western Classical tradition. These touchpoints are subtle, and certainly most of what happened in jazz probably would have happened without influence from classical modernists, but the point is that these guys were really and digging to try and find compositional and improvisational techniques that could take their music further.

That’s an important point here too. Improvisation wasn’t a very major part of the classical tradition after a certain point, whereas it is the whole point of jazz. Even crazy dense avant-garde savant jazz involves some kind of improvisational framework that makes some degree of intuitive sense. Technical and conceptual advances in jazz are always squeezed through the filter of “can we play this AND play around with it on the fly in a live setting?” That forces it to maintain some kind of logic beyond what makes sense on paper.

>>114651975
korean lesson for the yejibros (please point out any mistakes juseyo)

>의미 있게 살자
translation: let's live with purpose!
>의미
meaning, purpose
>있게
combination of 있다 (to have, to exist) and conjugation 게 which turns 있다 into an adverb
>살자
cominbation of 살다 and conjugation 자. 살다 is a verb meaning to live, 자 turns a verb into a (informal) suggestion as i suspect yeji is talking to her fans and therefore writes in a casual way. 살자 literally means "let's live"

the whole thing, directly translated, reads: meaning - have - live - let's. obviously english grammar is the other way around, so it's "let's live with meaning/purpose".

To me they were simply the last great hope of UK rock. >>114598735
Don't expect a rock album. I know that sounds obvious but it took years for TBHC to click for me because I was expecting a slow build into a fast, rapid, and climactic finish at the end. But its not about that. Instead, try and enjoy the ride. Songs like Star Treatment do have a loud "YEAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAH" at the end, but for me I find the peak of the song to be "Lounge singer shimmer". And for Batphone (the song that made TBHC click for me) it was really getting into the flow of the song that made the second "I'll be by the BATphone" resonate with me. At least for me, this is the mental change I had to make before I could really understand TBHC

posts.com:
It’s been 20 years since Korg released the microKorg, not bad for a little synth that might’ve seemed like a novelty at the time of its release on July 19, 2002. It’s quite the achievement considering the number of other synths has come and gone during this period such as the Alesis Micron, Akai Miniak, and DSI Evolver to name a few. Its production has outlasted Korg’s own successful run of MS-20 (late 1970’s to the 1980s) and Wavestation synths (during the 1990s), and enduring other synth royalty such as the Moog Minimoog or Yamaha’s string of DX-7 variations. The microKORG has become one of the best-selling synths of all time. After 20 years, the microKORG continues to sell well with many musicians across different genres embracing Korg’s living legend. So why does the microKorg continue to appeal? To commemorate this milestone, we take a look at why it has grown to become a classic.

Launched in 2002, Korg designed the microKorg based on their highly revered analog modelling synth the MS2000. Korg grabbed all the best bits from the MS2000, reduced its physical size, gave it a look that was reminiscent of synths from the 1970s and 1980s, made it highly affordable and hey presto, the microKorg was born.

The mini-keys would have to be a major factor in its appeal. Whether you like them or not doesn’t matter. 36 keys are far superior to 25 when you’re trying to fit three full octaves into a portable synth. It allows you to play with two hands or two fingers instead of having to continuously press the octave up/down buttons.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114639279
To a new generation, the microKorg introduced the vocoder. Even though there are only eight bands, setting up vocoders for a beginner can be challenging, but the microKorg made it ridiculously simple — the microphone is included, the built-in keys filter notes, and it is up and running with just a single push of a button.

Even though it is digital it simulates analogue, and it does a damn good job of it. Additionally, there is enough variety among the presets to keep you interested. Being able to browse through patches quickly is essential and its 128 factory preset sound patches divided into 8 groups make it easy to navigate.

Trance
Techno/House
Electronica
D’n’B/Breaks
Hip hop/Vintage
Retro
Special Effects/Hit
Vocoder

Korg seemed to have captured a wide variety of contrasting synth sounds that were appealing to a broad range of music styles, even those outside of electronic dance music.

Furthermore, all the best twiddles are conveniently close at hand thanks to the large knobs for cutoff, resonance, attack, and release. It gives you immediate pleasure. It also avoids the more tedious sequencing process but does have an arpeggiator, which, if you had to pick, is probably the quicker and more enjoyable of the two.

Additionally, the microKorg is feather-light, has a battery-operated option, the faux wood end cheeks make it ideal for the rapidly expanding interest in vintage synthesizers and it’s priced keenly; you get a touch of everything for not much!

When mini synths first came out, they weren’t intended to do much, but the microKorg was somewhat of a mini-revolution and based on the millions of musicians who have bought this synth, it still is.

>>114651884
Nos. 1 & 3 are not a thing. No. 2 is "palming" it. No. 4 is properly correct, but mostly from the context of classical guitar with lighter tension nylon strings, 2" wide, fat neck and classical sitting position. When playing with modern, slimmer necks and steel strings, 4 might not give you enough leverage for some fingerings, as you've already discovered. Indeed, palming it may be the only way to play certain fingerings, eg a D7 chord. This becomes more the case the larger your hands are (larger = longer/wider, not fatter). 4 gives you the most dexterity and access.

>>114608328
Gear up for my blog post:

Screaming Suicide, aka Atlas Rise II.
As a song it's ok, but it suffers from the same thing the Death Magneto and Hardwired albums did: clunky, ill fitting arrangements buttressed together.

The excessive hi hat counts and snare flams are grating. It's almost like this band (Lars) doesn't believe in creating space between the notes anymore; they don't let stuff ring out or breathe. Especially Lars, he just constantly plays nuisance notes. The drums are also way too loud in the mix, but this is the Metallica (Lars) way.

Essentially an Atlas Rise riff in A redux, and a fairly unremarkable Hammett solo. The riffs jangle instead of chug. It's Reload-type riffage if you listen. Stylistically, I suspect this is the best they can do now, and it's fucking sad.

Curiously, Trujillo gets a co-writing credit on this song, but I don't hear his musical prowess shine at all, so I'm at a loss as to what he contributed.

Surprisingly, Het's vocals and lyrics are the best part of this song, imo. Starting to think 72 Seasons would probably have made a better Hetfield solo album. It's all about his trauma by the looks of it, and he could probably find better musicians to collaborate with at this point.

The advertising agency-created cover art stinks. I hope I'm wrong, but this album smells suspiciously like a clunker already. I don't want to hear Fuel and Ain't My Bitch in E minor for the 6th album yet again.

This band is more popular than ever, but they lost their nous when they become pop stars in '91. I'm starting to think those first 5 albums were a fluke. Catch them on tour this year and meet them for the low price of $3k!

>>114649409
Their theory of phonetic organization, despite its pretentious name, is legitimately very cool and can lead to very soulful music.
The theory of phonetic organization is the belief that artists should begin with a sound and work their way up to the music, as opposed to starting with the music and working your way up to the sound. A typical song starts as a tune, generally articulated on guitar or piano, and then you build it into a full band arrangements. The Residents, however, just experimented with homemade instruments, out of tune instruments, instruments they didn’t know how to play, etc. and screwed around until discovering noises they liked, they then turned these noises into tunes. Their early work especially did this. Every single musician has screwed around with noises and thought “hey that sounds cool,” but usually it doesn’t lead to anything necessarily. Meet The Residents and Third Reich N Roll have a fun atmosphere of fresh loose articulation because of it. Honestly, I believe it had more impact on their enduring popularity than the theory of obscurity

>>114649599
>so is it basically, take timbre as the building blocks of the sound instead of melody?
Yes.
>what’s the theory of obscurity
The Residents claimed, especially in their earlier days, that they were instructed by an obscure Bavarian avant-garde composer named N. Senada, who articulated the theory of obscurity and the theory of phonetic organization. He also did other things in their mythology (e.g. he went on an arctic expedition and returned with a jar full of arctic air, inspiring the album Eskimo)
The theory of obscurity is that an artist can only produce the purest expression of their art when the expectations and influences of the outside world are not taken into consideration at all. Basically, don’t let the audience influence your work at all. This is why the Residents hide their identities and switch styles so frequently, so the audience never knows what to expect from a Residents album. They also made an album called Not Available, the plan was to record it in secrecy, and then not release it until they forgot they had made it, as the purest example of the theory of obscurity. It was recorded 1974, and released 1978

I also like how the droll sheen surrounding their music and art are underpinned by really dark and complex themes in their lyrics. Gingerbread Man, for instance.

And I like their commitment to being avant-garde not just for the sake of "lol we're weird and different." Their unusual approach creates genuinely interesting and original music.

Basically, Bach wrote polyphonic music (music with multiple simulations melodies) at a time when polyphonic composition was governed by a very strict ruleset. The brilliance of Bach was that his compositions were almost as complex as could ever be possible within that very narrow framework while still being very obviously satisfying logically/musically to anyone listening. There’s a simultaneous mathematical and sonic beauty to his work that’s just very hard to dislike.

Studying almost any of his works illustrates how much music you can squeeze out of what are in essence very basic and rigid harmonic frameworks. Musicians especially often really like his works because they are intricate enough to give you a serious technical workout but the individual components are just as musically satisfying played slower as they are fast, so it sounds good while practicing even when painfully slow.

The thing that blows my mind the most about Bach, especially his cantatas, is that from what it looks like his aim wasn't to create the greatest music the world has ever heard or to impress countless audiences, like the later composers (Mozart, Beethoven). He was merely doing his job as a Kantor and trying his best to musically illustrate the weekly or monthly religious lessons at his various church jobs.

If the Sunday readings required an illustration of beauty and grace then he could effortlessly write the most beautiful, moving, serene and life-affirming music the world will ever hear, and the opposite, if the church needed grief, suffering or even hellish terror to be illustrated than that was also easy for him to craft, creating some absolutely heartbreaking compositions, like the openings of BWV102 or BWV105. But the prowess and merit of these compositions wasn't the main goal, he was just doing his job the best he could, preaching and expressing his pious and passionate mind, however what was ordinary to Bach is extremely extra-ordinary to us mere mortals.

Take the BWV54 opening posted above, what we hear is a beautiful piano arrangement played in-front of a crowd, but it definitely wasn't written with that in mind. It's been extracted from a cantata, practically written for voices and ensemble, from the archives of some small church in the middle of a forest in bumfuck no-where Germany, where the weekly readings prompted the greatest musical genius to write music that will last as long as humanity will, if not longer. Nothing more and nothing less than that.

>>114648687
Yes, you can teach yourself drums. Holding your sticks right is very important. Take extra time on proper stick grip. Taking a few lessons should help if you find a good teacher. Drumeo and some free channels on YouTube are pretty good.
Electronic drums are okay. There are some things that you can't learn on electronic kits, though. If you hit an acoustic drum outside of the sweet spot on a head you will get unpleasant overtones. An electric kit only triggers samples and you will get the same sounds no matter where you hit the heads. So be mindful to hit the centers of the pads when you play. It will help cross over to acoustic drums (if you want to.)
Go for it. It is fun.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114648715
You will NOT be able to learn velocity or texture properly with an e-kit which are both super important if you want to eventually play acoustic. E-kits are getting really good with velocity and texture nowadays but it still is nowhere close to the true dynamics of an acoustic kit.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Also..
If you plan on getting a roland v-kit or already have one, consider replacing their cymbals with yamaha cymbals. Roland probably makes the best e-drums in the industry but Yamaha's cymbals are just objectively better every way. Roland cymbals feel just a few steps above Rock Band drum cymbals and within a few months of consistent playing your cymbals will already start to double register/glitch. Yeah it sucks to have to buy expensive cymbals on top of your already outrageously expensive Roland kit, but the experience in the end is just so much more worth it.

Musical literacy was much higher in the 1500-1800s than from the 1900s on
Basically, from the mass spread of the printing press to the mass spread of recorded music.
It was much more common for people to be able to play musical instruments and read sheet music than it is today, because it was the only way to enjoy music most of the time, play it yourself or read it. Listening to pro performers was a rare special occasion for the non rich, and even the rich couldn't choose to listen to a particular symphony a lot of times, they listened to whatever was played in the local opera house, so even the rich may only be able to listen to their favorite symphony a handful of times.

Recordings eliminated the need in most people of needing to know how to play an instrument and read sheet music in order to enjoy music.
Something similar is happening right now with software like Google translate, the number of people who learn a second language may decrease drastically, it won't be necessary anymore
